						<h1>What is DPI &amp; eDPI?</h1>

					=09
						<aside class=3D"meta" data-nosnippet=3D"">

        <div class=3D"post-title__meta">
        <div class=3D"post-title__meta__written-by">
        <p>
            Written by <a href=3D"https://prosettings.net/members/05c36f81c=
9db8f39cbc0fb14f289751b1df562ac/"><picture class=3D"avatar-picture edge-ima=
ges-container" style=3D"--content-visibility: auto; --height: 25px; --max-w=
idth: 25px; --width: 25px"><img alt=3D"Avatar photo" src=3D"https://prosett=
ings.net/cdn-cgi/image/dpr=3D1%2Cf=3Dauto%2Cfit=3Dcover%2Ch=3D25%2Cq=3D95%2=
Csharpen=3D1%2Cw=3D25/wp-content/uploads/cropped-lars-casual.png" class=3D"=
avatar avatar-25 photo edge-images-img edge-images-processed" height=3D"25"=
 width=3D"25" decoding=3D"async"></picture>Lars</a> |             Published=
 on <time datetime=3D"2022-08-21T18:11:18+02:00">Aug 21, 2022</time>
             | Last modified on <time datetime=3D"2023-09-15T12:06:09+00:00=
">Sep 15, 2023</time>        </p>
    </div>
   =20
       =20
</div></aside>=09

		</section>

				<div class=3D"center-container">

						<picture class=3D"edge-images-container" style=3D"--content-visibilit=
y: auto; --height: 360px; --max-width: 720px; --width: 720px"><img alt=3D""=
 class=3D"attachment-720x360 size-720x360 wp-image-141227 edge-images-proce=
ssed wp-post-image" decoding=3D"async" fetchpriority=3D"high" height=3D"360=
" src=3D"https://prosettings.net/cdn-cgi/image/dpr=3D1%2Cf=3Dauto%2Cfit=3Dc=
over%2Ch=3D360%2Cq=3D95%2Cw=3D720/wp-content/uploads/what-is-dpi-and-edpi.p=
ng" width=3D"720"></picture>

						<main class=3D"content">
			=09
<p>eDPI stands for =E2=80=98effective Dots Per Inch,=E2=80=99 which is a fo=
rmula used to calculate the effective sensitivity of any given player, rega=
rdless of hardware or software settings. The formula is DPI * ingame sens.<=
/p>



<p>In gaming, users can use many different hardware/software settings combi=
nations. One user might have his mouse set to be extremely sensitive at the=
 hardware level (which means he would have a high DPI; Dots Per Inch) with =
a very low ingame sensitivity, while another user might go for the reverse.=
 eDPI is a handy tool to compare the actual sensitivity of different setups=
 that takes all of these settings into account.</p>


<div class=3D"ez-toc-exclude"><div class=3D"article-summary-wrapper">
    <span>Highlights</span>
   =20
    <ul class=3D"article-summary">
        <li>DPI =3D Dots Per Inch; your mouse=E2=80=99s sensitivity on a ha=
rdware level</li><li>eDPI =3D DPI multiplied by ingame sensitivity</li><li>=
eDPI is used to easily compare =E2=80=98true sensitivities=E2=80=99 across =
different setups in the same game</li><li>eDPI cannot be used to compare ac=
ross games, since different games handle sensitivity differently</li>
    </ul>
</div></div>


<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-what-is-dpi"><span class=3D"ez-toc-s=
ection" id=3D"what-is-dpi"></span>What is DPI?<span class=3D"ez-toc-section=
-end"></span></h2>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p>DPI&nbsp;stands for Dots Per Inch. If you=E2=80=99ve got your mouse set =
at 1000 DPI it means that the mouse will =E2=80=98measure=E2=80=99 1000 poi=
nts of movement per inch that you move the mouse. The higher your DPI is, t=
he more your cursor moves when you move the mouse. The higher the DPI, the =
more =E2=80=98sensitive=E2=80=99 the mouse, from a hardware point of view. =
</p>



<p>DPI is always set on the mouse itself or via software (see <a href=3D"ht=
tps://prosettings.net/blog/how-to-find-dpi-and-change-it/">How to find DPI =
and change it</a>). In general, the DPI of your mouse will determine how se=
nsitive it is throughout your entire system. Almost all pro gamers use a DP=
I of 1600 or lower, since higher DPI settings can cause issues such as smoo=
thing (<a href=3D"https://prosettings.net/blog/what-is-mouse-smoothing/">Wh=
at is mouse smoothing?</a>).</p>



<p>Most mice have a DPI button located below the scroll wheel or on the und=
erside of the mouse, allowing you to cycle between different DPI settings o=
n the fly.</p>



<p><strong>Note: </strong>In PC gaming, CPI (Counts Per Inch) is used inter=
mittently with DPI.&nbsp;CPI is the same as DPI in this context.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-sensitivity"><span class=3D"ez-toc-s=
ection" id=3D"sensitivity"></span>Sensitivity<span class=3D"ez-toc-section-=
end"></span></h2>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<p>Sensitivity (or =E2=80=98sens=E2=80=99) is the&nbsp;<em>ingame</em>&nbsp=
;sensitivity setting. Contrary to DPI, this only applies in the game where =
you set it in, so you can use different sensitivities in different games at=
 the same time. Different games also use different ways of measuring sensit=
ivity, so =E2=80=981=E2=80=99 sensitivity in game A won=E2=80=99t necessari=
ly mean the same in game B. </p>



<picture class=3D"wp-block-image size-full edge-images-container" style=3D"=
--content-visibility: auto; --height: 397px; --max-width: 720px; --width: 7=
20px"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"720" height=3D"397" src=3D"https://p=
rosettings.net/cdn-cgi/image/dpr=3D1%2Cf=3Dauto%2Cfit=3Dcover%2Ch=3D397%2Cq=
=3D95%2Cw=3D720/wp-content/uploads/mouse-sensitivity-in-cs2.png" alt=3D"An =
example of mouse sensitivity in CS2" class=3D"wp-image-144006 edge-images-p=
rocessed"></picture>



<p>Looking at DPI or ingame sensitivity on its own to compare is usually a =
bad idea. Player A can have his mouse set to 1600 DPI with an ingame sensit=
ivity of 2, whilst player B can have her mouse set to 400 DPI with an ingam=
e sensitivity of 8. These look like wildly different configurations, but in=
 reality both players=E2=80=99 mice will be equally sensitive to movement. =
This is why we use eDPI to compare sensitivities across the same game.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-edpi"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section"=
 id=3D"edpi"></span>eDPI<span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<div class=3D"wp-block-group inline-notice inline-notice--info"><div class=
=3D"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is=
-layout-constrained">
<p><strong>eDPI</strong></p>



<p>DPI * Sensitivity<br><em><a href=3D"https://prosettings.net/library/how-=
to-find-change-dpi/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Find out=
 how to find your DPI</a></em></p>
</div></div>



<p>Since gamers like to compare settings, gear, and so forth, and comparing=
 raw sensitivity and DPI can get confusing we use eDPI when comparing =E2=
=80=98true sensitivities.=E2=80=99 </p>



<p>eDPI stands for effective Dots Per Inch, and it=E2=80=99s calculated by =
multiplying the mouse DPI with the ingame sensitivity. This gives gamers a =
way of comparing the true sensitivity of different players, regardless of t=
heir hardware or software settings. Note that eDPI is game-specific: differ=
ent games use different ways to calculate sensitivities, so eDPI is only us=
eful for comparing actual sensitivities of different players within the sam=
e game.</p>



<p>As an example, we=E2=80=99ve listed three different (fictional) players =
using the same eDPI, with drastically different settings.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-table"><table><thead><tr><th>Player</th><th>DPI</=
th><th>Ingame Sens</th><th>eDPI</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Player A</t=
d><td>400</td><td>2</td><td>400*2 =3D <strong>800</strong> </td></tr><tr><t=
d>Player B</td><td>800</td><td>1</td><td>800*1 =3D <strong>800</strong></td=
></tr><tr><td>Player C</td><td>1600</td><td>0.5</td><td>1600*0.5 =3D <stron=
g>800</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<p>As you can see, these three players use very different setups, but if yo=
u were to test all three setups, you wouldn=E2=80=99t notice a difference i=
n the actual, real-life sensitivity of their mouse setups. For this reason,=
 eDPI gets used to compare effective sensitivities.</p>

			</main>

